VALUES
(44, 15, 27, 44, 15, 22, 22, 'Judas and Silas', 'Sending of Judas and Silas', 'Both passages emphasize the sending of Judas and Silas to Antioch. Acts 15:22 introduces them as chosen men, while Acts 15:27 confirms their role in communicating the same message.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 27, 44, 15, 32, 32, 'Judas and Silas', 'Connection of Judas and Silas', 'This connection highlights the role of Judas and Silas as messengers. Both passages emphasize their involvement in delivering important messages to the brethren.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 27, 63, 1, 12, 12, NULL, 'Communication and Joy', 'This connection highlights the importance of direct communication in both passages. Acts emphasizes speaking face to face, while 2 John expresses a desire to communicate personally for the sake of joy.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 27, 64, 1, 13, 13, NULL, 'Communication of Messages', 'This connection highlights the theme of conveying messages. In Acts 15:27, the emphasis is on sharing information verbally, while in 3 John 1:13, the author chooses not to write extensively, suggesting a preference for direct communication.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 28, 40, 11, 30, 30, 'no greater burden', 'Connection of Burden and Ease', 'This connection highlights the theme of burdens in both passages. Acts 15:28 speaks of laying no greater burden, while Matthew 11:30 emphasizes that Jesus'' burden is light.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 28, 43, 16, 13, 13, 'Holy Ghost', 'Guidance of the Holy Spirit', 'This connection highlights the role of the Holy Spirit in guiding believers. Both passages emphasize the Spirit''s authority in determining what is necessary for the community and revealing truth.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 28, 66, 2, 24, 24, 'no greater burden', 'Burden in Early Church Teachings', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of imposing no greater burden on believers. Acts 15:28 states that the Holy Spirit and the apostles decided to lay upon the Gentiles no greater burden, while Revelation 2:24 assures the faithful in Thyatira that they will not be given another burden.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 28, 46, 14, 37, 37, 'it seemed good to the Holy Ghost', 'Authority of the Holy Spirit', 'This connection highlights the role of the Holy Spirit in guiding decisions and affirming teachings. Both passages emphasize the importance of recognizing divine authority in the instructions given to believers.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 28, 60, 1, 12, 12, 'Holy Ghost', 'Connection of the Holy Spirit', 'Both passages emphasize the role of the Holy Ghost in guiding believers. Acts 15:28 mentions the Holy Ghost''s approval in decision-making, while 1 Peter 1:12 highlights the Holy Ghost''s involvement in preaching the gospel.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 28, 44, 5, 32, 32, 'Holy Ghost', 'Role of the Holy Ghost', 'This connection highlights the role of the Holy Ghost in guiding believers. Both passages emphasize the Holy Ghost''s involvement in the community''s decisions and obedience.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 28, 44, 15, 8, 8, 'Holy Ghost', 'Connection of the Holy Ghost', 'Both passages emphasize the role of the Holy Ghost in guiding the early church. Acts 15:28 mentions the Holy Ghost''s approval, while Acts 15:8 highlights God''s witness through the Holy Ghost.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 29, 44, 15, 20, 20, NULL, 'Connection of Abstaining Instructions', 'Both passages emphasize the need to abstain from pollutions of idols, fornication, and blood. This connection highlights the continuity in the instructions given to the early believers regarding dietary and moral practices.', 'theme', 0.426, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 29, 44, 21, 25, 25, NULL, 'Connection of Gentile Guidelines', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of abstaining from certain practices, specifically ''things offered to idols, and from blood, and from strangled, and from fornication.'' This connection highlights the continuity of guidelines for Gentile believers in the early church.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 29, 66, 2, 14, 14, NULL, 'Connection of Idolatry and Fornication', 'Both passages emphasize the prohibition against eating things sacrificed unto idols and committing fornication. This connection highlights a consistent moral teaching regarding idolatry and sexual immorality within the early church.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 29, 66, 2, 20, 20, NULL, 'Connection of Fornication and Idolatry', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of abstaining from fornication and eating things sacrificed to idols. Acts 15:29 warns against these practices, while Revelation 2:20 addresses their occurrence within the church.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 29, 3, 17, 14, 14, 'from blood', 'Connection of Blood and Abstinence', 'Both passages emphasize the prohibition of consuming blood. Acts 15:29 instructs abstaining from blood, echoing Leviticus 17:14''s command against eating blood, highlighting a consistent theme of dietary restrictions.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 29, 46, 10, 18, 20, 'meats offered to idols', 'Connection on Idolatry and Sacrifice', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of abstaining from meats offered to idols. Acts 15:29 warns against such practices, while 1 Corinthians 10:20 clarifies that these sacrifices are made to devils, not God. This connection highlights the shared theme of avoiding idolatrous practices.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 29, 45, 14, 20, 21, 'from which if ye keep yourselves', 'Abstaining from Offending Others', 'This connection highlights the theme of abstaining from actions that may cause others to stumble in their faith. Both passages emphasize the importance of considering the impact of one''s choices on fellow believers.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 30, 44, 6, 2, 2, 'gathered the multitude together', 'Gathering the Multitude', 'Both passages emphasize the gathering of the multitude. In Acts 15:30, the multitude is gathered to receive an important message, while in Acts 6:2, the multitude is called together for a decision regarding service roles.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 30, 44, 16, 4, 4, 'delivered the epistle', 'Delivery of Apostolic Decrees', 'Both passages emphasize the act of delivering decrees from the apostles. Acts 15:30 mentions the delivery of an epistle, while Acts 16:4 refers to delivering decrees ordained by the apostles.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 30, 44, 21, 22, 22, NULL, 'Gathering of the Multitude', 'Both passages emphasize the gathering of the multitude. In Acts 15:30, the multitude is gathered to hear the epistle, while in Acts 21:22, it is noted that the multitude must come together to hear news of Paul''s arrival.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 30, 44, 23, 33, 33, 'delivered the epistle', 'Delivery of Epistles', 'This connection highlights the act of delivering epistles in both passages. In Acts 15:30, the epistle is delivered to the multitude, while in Acts 23:33, it is delivered to the governor, showing a thematic continuity in the communication of important messages.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 31, 48, 2, 4, 5, 'rejoiced for the consolation', 'Connection of Rejoicing and Truth', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of liberty in Christ and the joy that comes from the truth of the gospel. The rejoicing in Acts 15:31 reflects the consolation found in the freedom from bondage that Paul defends in Galatians 2:4-5.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 31, 48, 5, 1, 1, 'rejoiced for the consolation', 'Connection of Freedom and Consolation', 'This connection highlights the theme of freedom and joy in Christ. Both passages emphasize the importance of standing firm in the liberty provided by Christ, which brings consolation to believers.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 31, 50, 3, 3, 3, 'rejoiced for the consolation', 'Rejoicing in Spiritual Assurance', 'Both passages emphasize rejoicing as a response to spiritual truths. Acts 15:31 highlights joy from consolation, while Philippians 3:3 connects rejoicing with worshiping God in spirit.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 31, 44, 15, 1, 1, NULL, 'Salvation and Consolation Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of salvation. The teaching in Acts 15:1 suggests a requirement for circumcision for salvation, while Acts 15:31 reflects the joy and consolation that comes from understanding true salvation without such requirements.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 31, 44, 15, 10, 10, 'rejoiced for the consolation', 'Connection of Yoke and Consolation', 'Both passages emphasize the burden of the yoke placed on the disciples. The rejoicing in consolation suggests relief from this burden, indicating a positive response to the alleviation of the yoke.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 32, 44, 11, 23, 23, 'exhorted the brethren', 'Exhortation and Confirmation', 'Both passages emphasize the act of exhortation to encourage believers. In Acts 15:32, Judas and Silas confirm the brethren, while in Acts 11:23, the exhortation is aimed at encouraging steadfastness in the faith.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 32, 44, 13, 1, 1, 'prophets', 'Connection of Prophets in Antioch', 'This connection highlights the presence of prophets in both passages. Acts 15:32 mentions Judas and Silas as prophets who encouraged the brethren, while Acts 13:1 identifies prophets in the church at Antioch, suggesting a continuity of prophetic ministry.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 32, 52, 3, 2, 2, 'exhorted the brethren with many words', 'Encouragement and Comfort in Faith', 'This connection highlights the theme of providing support to believers. Both passages emphasize the role of individuals in establishing and comforting the faith of others.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 32, 52, 5, 14, 14, 'exhorted the brethren', 'Exhortation and Support in Community', 'This connection highlights the theme of exhortation and support within the Christian community. Both passages emphasize the importance of encouraging and strengthening fellow believers in their faith.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 32, 60, 5, 1, 1, 'exhorted the brethren', 'Exhortation and Leadership', 'This connection highlights the role of exhortation in leadership within the early church. Both passages emphasize the importance of encouraging and confirming the brethren, linking the prophetic role of Judas and Silas to the exhortation of elders.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 32, 60, 5, 10, 10, 'confirmed them', 'Encouragement and Strengthening', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of strengthening believers. Acts 15:32 mentions confirming the brethren, while 1 Peter 5:10 speaks of making believers perfect and establishing them after suffering.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 32, 23, 35, 3, 4, NULL, 'Encouragement and Strengthening', 'This connection highlights the theme of strengthening and confirming the weak and fearful. Both passages emphasize the importance of encouragement in the face of fear and weakness.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 33, 46, 16, 11, 11, 'let go in peace', 'Connection of Peace in Scripture', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of being sent forth in peace. In Acts, the brethren are let go in peace, while in 1 Corinthians, there is a call to conduct someone forth in peace.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 33, 44, 16, 36, 36, NULL, 'Theme of Departure in Peace', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of departing in peace. In Acts 15:33, the brethren let the apostles go in peace, while in Acts 16:36, the magistrates instruct Paul to depart and go in peace.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 33, 58, 11, 31, 31, NULL, 'Connection of Peace in Scripture', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of peace. In Acts, the brethren send the apostles away in peace, while in Hebrews, Rahab receives the spies with peace, highlighting the significance of peace in faith and community.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 33, 1, 26, 29, 29, 'let go in peace', 'Peaceful Departures', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of departing in peace. In Acts, the brethren send the apostles away in peace, while in Genesis, the individuals express their goodwill by sending someone away in peace. This connection highlights the importance of peaceful resolutions in relationships.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 33, 2, 4, 18, 18, 'let go in peace', 'Peaceful Departures', 'Both passages emphasize a peaceful departure. In Acts, the brethren let them go in peace, while in Exodus, Jethro tells Moses to go in peace.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 33, 41, 5, 34, 34, 'go in peace', 'Connection of Peace and Healing', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of peace. In Acts 15:33, the phrase ''let go in peace'' suggests a sense of resolution, while Mark 5:34''s ''go in peace'' follows a healing, indicating restoration and wholeness.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 33, 63, 1, 10, 10, 'let go in peace', 'Peace and Reception', 'This connection highlights the theme of how believers should interact with one another. Acts 15:33 mentions being let go in peace, while 2 John 1:10 advises against receiving those who do not bring the correct doctrine, emphasizing discernment in fellowship.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 35, 51, 1, 28, 28, 'teaching and preaching the word of the Lord', 'Teaching and Preaching Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the act of teaching and preaching. Acts 15:35 mentions Paul and Barnabas teaching, while Colossians 1:28 speaks of preaching and teaching every man.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 35, 55, 4, 2, 2, 'teaching and preaching the word of the Lord', 'Connection of Preaching and Teaching', 'This connection highlights the importance of preaching and teaching the word of the Lord in both passages. Acts 15:35 mentions Paul and Barnabas teaching, while 2 Timothy 4:2 emphasizes the call to preach the word.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 35, 40, 28, 19, 20, 'teaching and preaching the word of the Lord', 'Teaching and Preaching Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the act of teaching. Acts 15:35 mentions ''teaching and preaching the word of the Lord,'' which aligns with the directive in Matthew 28:19-20 to ''teach all nations.'' This connection highlights the continuity of the mission to spread the teachings of Jesus.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 35, 44, 13, 1, 1, 'teaching and preaching the word of the Lord', 'Teaching and Preaching in Antioch', 'Both passages emphasize the role of teaching and preaching in the church at Antioch. Acts 15:35 mentions Paul and Barnabas continuing this work, while Acts 13:1 identifies Barnabas as a teacher in that same community.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 35, 44, 8, 4, 4, 'preaching the word', 'Preaching the Word Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the act of preaching the word. In Acts 15:35, Paul and Barnabas are teaching and preaching, while Acts 8:4 describes those scattered preaching the word everywhere.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 35, 54, 2, 7, 7, 'teaching and preaching the word of the Lord', 'Connection of Preaching and Teaching', 'Both passages emphasize the role of preaching and teaching. In Acts, Paul and Barnabas are engaged in teaching, while in 1 Timothy, the speaker identifies as a preacher and teacher of the Gentiles.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 36, 44, 13, 4, 4, 'where we have preached the word', 'Missionary Journeys of Paul and Barnabas', 'This connection highlights the continuation of Paul and Barnabas''s missionary efforts. In Acts 15:36, Paul expresses a desire to revisit cities where they previously preached, as noted in Acts 13:4, where they began their journey to Cyprus.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 36, 44, 14, 6, 6, 'visit our brethren in every city', 'Connection of Missionary Journeys', 'This connection highlights Paul''s desire to revisit cities where he previously preached, specifically Lystra and Derbe mentioned in Acts 14:6. Both passages emphasize the ongoing mission to strengthen the faith of believers in these regions.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 36, 47, 11, 28, 28, 'visit our brethren', 'Concern for the Churches', 'This connection highlights Paul''s desire to ''visit our brethren'' and Barnabas''s role in caring for the churches. Both passages emphasize the ongoing responsibility and care for the communities established through their ministry.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 36, 2, 4, 18, 18, 'visit our brethren', 'Visiting Brethren Theme', 'This connection highlights the theme of returning to visit brethren. Both Paul and Moses express a desire to check on their respective communities, emphasizing care and concern for their well-being.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 36, 45, 1, 11, 11, 'visit our brethren in every city', 'Connection of Spiritual Care', 'This connection highlights the theme of visiting and caring for believers. Both passages emphasize the importance of establishing and supporting the faith of others.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 36, 52, 3, 10, 11, 'visit our brethren', 'Connection of Paul’s Visits', 'This connection highlights Paul''s desire to visit and strengthen the faith of believers. Both passages emphasize the importance of seeing and supporting fellow Christians in their spiritual journey.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 36, 24, 23, 2, 2, 'visit our brethren', 'Visitation and Care for Flock', 'This connection highlights the theme of visiting and caring for the people. In Acts, Paul expresses a desire to ''visit'' the brethren, while in Jeremiah, the Lord condemns those who have ''not visited'' His people.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 37, 44, 12, 12, 12, 'John, whose surname was Mark', 'Connection of John Mark', 'Both passages emphasize John, whose surname was Mark, linking him to Barnabas'' decision to take him along. This connection highlights the significance of Mark in the early Christian community.', 'keyword', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 37, 44, 12, 25, 25, 'John, whose surname was Mark', 'Connection of John Mark''s Role', 'Both passages emphasize Barnabas taking John, whose surname was Mark, with him. This highlights the continuity of John Mark''s involvement in the early ministry.', 'keyword', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 37, 51, 4, 10, 10, 'John, whose surname was Mark', 'Connection of John Mark', 'This connection highlights the relationship between Barnabas and Mark, as Barnabas is identified as Mark''s uncle in Colossians. Both passages emphasize the significance of Mark in the early Christian community.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 37, 55, 4, 11, 11, 'John, whose surname was Mark', 'Connection of John Mark''s Role', 'This connection highlights the importance of John Mark in both passages. In Acts, Barnabas''s determination to take Mark indicates his significance, while in 2 Timothy, Paul acknowledges Mark''s profitability for ministry.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 37, 57, 1, 24, 24, 'John, whose surname was Mark', 'Connection of John Mark', 'This connection highlights the presence of John Mark, referred to as ''Mark'' in Philemon, indicating his role as a fellow laborer in the early church. Both passages emphasize the significance of Mark in the ministry alongside Barnabas and Paul.', 'keyword', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 38, 44, 13, 13, 13, 'departed from them from Pamphylia', 'Paul''s Disagreement Over John Mark', 'This connection highlights Paul''s concern over John departing from them in Pamphylia, which is referenced in both passages. The first passage reflects Paul''s reluctance to take John Mark again due to his previous departure.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 38, 19, 78, 9, 9, 'went not with them to the work', 'Turning Back in Battle', 'This connection highlights the theme of retreat in both passages. Paul’s decision not to take Mark reflects a sense of abandonment similar to the children of Ephraim turning back in battle.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 38, 20, 25, 19, 19, 'who departed from them', 'Faithfulness in Relationships', 'This connection highlights the theme of trustworthiness in relationships. Paul''s reluctance to take Mark, who had previously departed, reflects the caution advised in Proverbs regarding reliance on an unfaithful person.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 38, 42, 14, 27, 34, NULL, 'Cost of Discipleship', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of commitment in discipleship. Paul''s decision regarding Mark reflects the necessity of perseverance in ministry, paralleling Jesus'' teaching on counting the cost of following Him.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 38, 59, 1, 8, 8, 'not good to take him with them', 'Instability and Commitment', 'This connection highlights the theme of instability in commitment. Paul''s decision regarding John Mark reflects a concern for reliability, paralleling the idea that a ''double minded man is unstable'' in his actions.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 38, 42, 9, 61, 61, 'went not with them to the work', 'Commitment to Following Jesus', 'This connection highlights the theme of commitment in following Jesus. In both passages, there is a hesitation to fully engage in the work of discipleship, as seen in Paul''s reluctance regarding Mark and the man''s desire to bid farewell.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 39, 51, 4, 10, 10, 'Barnabas took Mark', 'Connection Between Barnabas and Mark', 'This connection highlights the relationship between Barnabas and Mark, as Barnabas took Mark with him after their contention. In Colossians, Mark is identified as Barnabas''s sister''s son, indicating a familial link.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 39, 21, 7, 20, 20, 'contention was so sharp between them', 'Human Fallibility and Conflict', 'This connection highlights the theme of human imperfection and conflict. In Acts, the sharp contention between Paul and Barnabas reflects the reality that even devoted individuals can disagree and separate, paralleling Ecclesiastes'' assertion that no just man is without sin.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 39, 44, 4, 36, 36, 'Cyprus', 'Barnabas and Cyprus Connection', 'Both passages emphasize Barnabas''s connection to Cyprus. In Acts 15:39, Barnabas departs to Cyprus, while Acts 4:36 identifies him as a Levite from Cyprus.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 39, 59, 3, 2, 2, 'the contention was so sharp', 'Contention and Offense in Speech', 'This connection highlights the theme of contention and offense. In Acts, the sharp contention between Barnabas and Paul reflects the broader principle in James about how we offend in many things, particularly through words.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 39, 45, 7, 18, 21, 'the contention was so sharp', 'Conflict and Inner Struggle', 'This connection highlights the theme of contention and struggle. In Acts, the sharp contention leads to separation, while Romans discusses the internal conflict of wanting to do good but failing. Both passages emphasize the struggle inherent in relationships and personal conduct.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 39, 44, 6, 1, 1, 'the contention was so sharp', 'Conflict and Division in Community', 'This connection highlights the theme of contention and division within the early Christian community. Both passages emphasize how disagreements can lead to separation and murmuring among believers.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 39, 19, 106, 33, 33, 'contention was so sharp between them', 'Contention and Provocation', 'This connection highlights the theme of conflict arising from unadvised speech. Both passages emphasize the consequences of provoking others, leading to separation and contention.', 'theme', 0.293, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 40, 44, 15, 22, 22, NULL, 'Connection of Chosen Men', 'Both passages emphasize the selection of Silas as a chosen companion for Paul. Acts 15:22 identifies Silas as a chief man among the brethren, while Acts 15:40 highlights Paul''s choice of him for the mission.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 40, 44, 11, 23, 23, 'grace of God', 'Connection of Grace in Acts', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of grace, with Acts 15:40 mentioning the ''grace of God'' in relation to Paul''s mission and Acts 11:23 highlighting the joy of witnessing ''the grace of God.'' This connection highlights the importance of grace in the early church''s mission and community.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 40, 46, 15, 10, 10, 'grace of God', 'Connection of Grace in Paul', 'This connection highlights the theme of grace in both passages. In Acts 15:40, Paul is recommended ''unto the grace of God,'' while in 1 Corinthians 15:10, Paul emphasizes that he is what he is ''by the grace of God.''', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 40, 47, 13, 14, 14, 'the grace of God', 'Connection of Grace in Scripture', 'This connection highlights the theme of grace present in both passages. In Acts, Paul is recommended ''unto the grace of God,'' while in 2 Corinthians, the grace of the Lord Jesus Christ is emphasized.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 40, 55, 4, 22, 22, 'grace of God', 'Connection of Grace in Ministry', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of grace in the context of ministry. In Acts, Paul is recommended unto the grace of God, while in 2 Timothy, grace is extended to Timothy, highlighting its importance in their respective ministries.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 15, 40, 56, 3, 15, 15, 'grace of God', 'Connection of Grace in Ministry', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of grace in the context of ministry and relationships within the church. Acts 15:40 mentions being recommended unto the grace of God, while Titus 3:15 concludes with a blessing of grace for all.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
